					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sophosblitz" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(327981); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=327981&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182995" alt="SophosBlitz" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=327981)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sophosblitz" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(327981); return false;" >SophosBlitz</a></span> <span class="odate time_1302431142 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 Apr 2011 10:25</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1120989">
									

<p>Despite the length of the article, I didn't have any problem reading through it one go. Unlike a lot of tl;dr's one might find, it was interesting enough that its length did not impact its narrative. I initially thought that the article would be too sciene fiction-y for its own good but after reading everything, I think it has enough creep to scare plenty of people.</p>
<p>The article is well-written and has the clinical tone down right. It gives you a progressive step-by-step explanation of how things should be handled in a concise manner so that it wasn't boring, and doesn't leave anything important out in the description. Personally, I was hooked by the end of the second paragraph and was sold while reading the reproduction document. I really loved the extra notes and conversation snippets.</p>
<p>The lengthy article is also a nice change of pace. I think we've had too many articles recently that pointlessly spent too many words describing how to lock something up or were just too short in general; there's a nice hint of ADD here and there. Plenty of our high-rated SCPs are lengthy and I think people shouldn't be afraid to write longer articles as long as they're well-written.</p>
<p>Also to Bland's comment about needing a picture, I really don't think a picture is needed for this article specifically. Personally, I think that any picture (be it the SCP, scenery, or unrelated) would just be glaringly obvious that it doesn't fit in the article, and put bias goggles over someone reading the article for the first time, confusing them. It'd be like suggesting that Able's article needs a picture too because of its length, before or after the Clef edit. Some things are better left to the description and imagination.</p>

							</div>

								
					
